    "answer_id" : 58837485,
    "question_id" : 136419,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In Java version 8+ can (advised to) use <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/package-summary.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">java.time</a> library. <a href=\"https://www.iso.org/iso-8601-date-and-time-format.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">ISO 8601</a> sets standard way to write dates: <code>YYYY-MM-DD</code> and <code>java.time.Instant</code> uses it, so (for <code>UTC</code>):</p>\n\n<pre><code>import java.time.Instant;\nint myYear = Integer.parseInt(Instant.now().toString().substring(0,4));\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>P.S. just in case (and shorted for getting <code>String</code>, not <code>int</code>), using <code>Calendar</code> looks better and can be made zone-aware.</p>\n"
